<DOC><DOCNO> AP880308-0007 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0043EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p BC-MarylandAt-A-Glance     03-08 0229</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Maryland At-A-Glance,240</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are the methods for pickingdelegates from Maryland to attend the 1988 Democratic andRepublican national conventions this summer.</TEXT><HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, RichardGephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon   Pledged delegates: 67   Super delegates: 10   Total: 77   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Tuesday, March 8 and Tuesday, May 17   Maryland's 44 Democratic National Convention delegates fromcongressional districts will be chosen directly from the March 8primary ballot.   The state's remaining 23 pledged national convention delegateswill be allocated among the presidential candidates in proportionto the results of the primary.</TEXT><HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: George Bush, Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, PatRobertson, Pete du Pont, Alexander Haig   Delegates: 41   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Tuesday, March 8 and Saturday, May 14   Maryland Republicans elect 24 of their national conventiondelegates directly from the March 8 primary ballot.   Those delegates are awarded on a winner-take-all basis in eachof the eight congressional districts.   Maryland's remaining 17 delegates at-large are awarded on awinner-take-all basis to the presidential candidate who carries thestate in the primary. The individuals to serve as at-largedelegates are picked at the state GOP spring convention May 13-14.</TEXT></DOC>